article.headline: Louisiana Tech 67, Illinois 61
article.story:
CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech coach Kurt Budke says he
takes his team on the road early in the season to face adversity.

Adversity came Monday night as a 6:51 scoring drought late in
the second half, but the 12th-ranked Lady Techsters held on to beat
Illinois 67-61.

"I was really proud the team was able to fight through it,"
Budke said. The Lady Techsters (2-0) missed nine straight shots as
they watched a 16-point lead drop to two points with 1:45
remaining.

The teams traded missed shots and free throws until, with 22
seconds remaining and Illinois trailing 64-61, the Illini turned
the ball over on an errant pass.

They never got another shot as Lakiste Barkus hit three of four
free throws to ice the game.

Barkus finished with 16 points to lead the Lady Techsters. Trina
Frierson and Erica Smith-Taylor scored 14 points each and Amisha
Carter had 13.

"It was two teams fighting and scrapping for everything they
could get," Budke said. "At times it was tough to make a pass."

Illinois (1-1) committed 26 turnovers and Louisiana Tech had 17.
A half dozen times during the game, one team would take the ball
away only to have the favor returned before a shot went up.

"It's kind of tough when someone's just giving it and hustling
and all in your face not to turn over the ball," said
Smith-Taylor.

Tiffanie Guthrie scored 23 points and grabbed 11 rebounds for
Illinois. Angelina Williams scored 11 and Erin Wigley had 10.
Aminata Yanni, who scored 27 points in Illinois' first game, was
held to 6 points.

Illinois was able to hit only one of eight 3-point attempts.
Tech hit six of 19.

"We felt that was one part of the game we had to take away from
them," Budke said. "We hit some big ones tonight when we needed
them."

Illinois also came back from two 8-point deficits to tie the
game.

"This kind of a game this early really helps us as a measuring
stick of where we need to be," said Illinois coach Theresa Grentz.
